<span id="freeTextContainer7410977782916313792">A book with a lot of promise that fails miserably. What captured my attention in the beginning was the prose style...it was very evocative but then it came to drown in its over reliance on similes...that repeat themselves over and over and over.<br/>The story itself started good but became unendingly episodic and cliche. The serial killer narrative and coming of age narratives never gelled. Characterizations were a little interesting but this was lost in a story that went nowhere, I stopped reading w</span>
  <span id="freeText7410977782916313792" style="display:none">A book with a lot of promise that fails miserably. What captured my attention in the beginning was the prose style...it was very evocative but then it came to drown in its over reliance on similes...that repeat themselves over and over and over.<br />The story itself started good but became unendingly episodic and cliche. The serial killer narrative and coming of age narratives never gelled. Characterizations were a little interesting but this was lost in a story that went nowhere, I stopped reading when he met Brigid (I just could not take anymore), and a style that was too heavy and too loaded with similes...more interesting metaphors would have helped break it up some.<br />The slow pace would have been more interesting if the introspection went beyond the obvious...almost cliche in its nature.<br />It was a disappointing book because I had such high expectations after reading the first chapter...but it faded quickly after this.<br />Not recommended...but I did not hate it either....luke warm is my appraisal. </span>
